## If you are issuing mdoc credentials

If you are issuing mdoc-based credentials, you also need to manage a Document Signer certificate in addition to your JWT signing key pair.

Your Document Signer certificate is issued under your IACA (Issuing Authority Certificate Authority) root and is used to sign the Mobile Security Object (MSO) inside each mdoc credential. Unlike a JWT signing key, the Document Signer key and its certificate chain are embedded directly in the signed credential — so GOV.UK Wallet and verifiers can check the certificate chain without needing to call your endpoints.

Key management requirements for mdoc Document Signer certificates:

- You must rotate your Document Signer certificate before it expires. Plan your rotation schedule to avoid any gap in signing capability.
- A retiring Document Signer certificate must remain valid (not revoked) for the full lifetime of any credentials signed with it. If you revoke a Document Signer certificate while credentials signed with it are still in use, those credentials will become unverifiable.
- Your IACA root certificate must remain registered with the GOV.UK Wallet trust infrastructure for the same period.

Contact the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding team to register a new Document Signer certificate or to notify them of a planned certificate rotation. See [certificate requirements](/issue-a-credential/mdoc/#certificate-requirements) for technical requirements.

| Key State | Description                                                                                                                                         |
|-----------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Created   | A key pair is generated with an activation date in the future. It is not yet used for signing.                                                      |
| Active    | A key becomes active on the activation date, and enabled for signing and verifying the VC. There must not be multiple keys active at the same time. |
| Inactive  | A key becomes inactive past its expiration date or time. The public key will still be valid for verifying the VC.                                   |
| Revoked   | A key is destroyed and removed from the issuer’s server, and is not valid for signing or verifying the signatures.                                  |